'''Martín Zubimendi Ibáñez''' (born 2 February 1999) is a Spanish professional [[footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].

Zubimendi began his career at [[Real Sociedad]], making his first-team debut in 2019. He made over 200 appearances and won the [[2019–20 Copa del Rey]] with the club. In July 2025, he signed for Arsenal for a reported initial fee of £55.8m.

Zubimendi made his senior debut for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in 2021, having previously represented them at various youth levels. He was part of Spain's victorious squad in [[UEFA Euro 2024]], as well as the [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals]].

==Early life==
Zubimendi was born in [[San Sebastián]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Corrigan |first=Dermot |title=Martin Zubimendi: The coach's midfielder and a 'complete' player |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6429219/2025/07/21/martin-zubimendi-arsenal-transfer-background/ |website=[[The Athletic]] |access-date=12 May 2026 |date=21 July 2025}}</ref> He is an only child.<ref>{{cite web |last=Castelao |first=Eduardo J. |title=Martín Zubimendi: "Algunas entrevistas me han provocado momentos incómodos, por eso a veces prefiero evitarlas" |url=https://www.elmundo.es/deportes/futbol/mundial-de-futbol/2025/10/09/68e7a1c6e9cf4a74438b45b3.html |website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |access-date=13 May 2026 |language=es |date=9 October 2025}}</ref> His mother is a teacher and his father is a retired university professor.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ortiz de Lazcano |first=Javier |title=Martín Zubimendi: "De niño quería parecerme a Xabi Alonso" |url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2024/07/04/martin-zubimendi-nino-queria-parecerme-xabi-alonso/00031720100682913501346.htm |website=[[La Voz de Galicia]] |access-date=12 May 2026 |language=es |date=4 July 2024}}</ref> He attended {{ill|Zurriola Ikastola|eu}} in San Sebastián.<ref>{{cite web |last=Parra |first=Pablo |title=El exprofesor de ajedrez de Zubimendi revela su secreto mejor guardado: "Veía antes que nadie lo que iba a pasar" |url=https://www.marca.com/radio/2025/11/14/exprofesor-ajedrez-zubimendi-revela-secreto-mejor-guardado-veia-nadie-iba-pasar.html |website=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |access-date=3 June 2026 |language=es |date=14 November 2025}}</ref> In addition to football, he also played [[chess]] in his youth, becoming a youth champion of [[Gipuzkoa]] at the age of 11.<ref>{{cite web |last=Asprón |first=Javier |title=Zubimendi no quiso ser Busquets |url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/zubimendi-quiso-busquets-20231103185308-nt.html |website=[[Diario ABC]] |access-date=12 May 2026 |language=es |date=3 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Romero |first=Abraham P. |title=Zubimendi, el cerebro del ajedrez y del balón por el que suspira media Europa: el "no" al Liverpool, su "ídolo" Xabi, el interés del Madrid... |url=https://www.elmundo.es/deportes/futbol/2025/02/25/67bcba2fe9cf4a0e218b457f.html |website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |access-date=3 June 2026 |language=es |date=25 February 2025}}</ref> He played for local football team [[Antiguoko]] in the Donosti Cup from 2006 to 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.donosticup.com/en/ten-players-who-will-play-upcoming-cup-finals-cartuja-have-common-having-participated-donosti-cup |title=Ten players who will play in the upcoming Cup finals at La Cartuja have in common having participated in the Donosti Cup! |publisher=Donosti Cup |date=7 April 2021 }}</ref><ref name="Lowe-2022">{{cite web |last=Lowe |first=Sid |title=Real Sociedad's Martín Zubimendi: 'Xabi Alonso is an idol, a role model' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/sep/08/real-sociedad-martin-zubimendi-xabi-alonso-manchester-united |website=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=12 May 2026 |date=8 September 2022}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Real Sociedad===
Zubimendi joined [[Real Sociedad]]'s youth setup in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cadenaser.com/emisora/2020/06/26/radio_san_sebastian/1593182504_401676.html|title=Zubimendi llega para quedarse|trans-title=Zubimendi arrives to stay|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=es|date=26 June 2020|accessdate=28 June 2020}}</ref> He made his senior debut with [[Real Sociedad C]] on 27 August 2016, playing the last seven minutes in a 0–0 [[Tercera División]] home draw against [[SCD Durango|Durango]].{{citation needed|date=August 2021}}

On 25 July 2018, Zubimendi renewed his contract until 2022, and was definitely promoted to [[Real Sociedad B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda División B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/real-sociedad/20180725/451101213696/la-real-renueva-a-martin-zubimendi-hasta-2022.html|title=La Real renueva a Martín Zubimendi hasta 2022|trans-title=Real renew Martín Zubimendi until 2022|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|date=25 July 2018|accessdate=28 June 2020}}</ref> The following 28 April, he made his first team – and [[La Liga]] – debut, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Rubén Pardo (footballer)|Rubén Pardo]] in a 2–1 home win over [[Getafe CF|Getafe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/04/28/primera/1556471966_052236.html|title=La Real respira y complica la Champions al Getafe|trans-title=Real breathe and complicate Getafe's Champions place|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=es|date=28 April 2019|accessdate=28 June 2020}}</ref> On 24 July 2020, he renewed his contract with the ''Txuri-urdin'' until 2025, being definitively promoted to the main squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/until-2025|title=Until 2025|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=24 July 2020|accessdate=8 August 2020}}</ref>

On 24 February 2022, Zubimendi scored his first goal in European competitions in a 3–1 home defeat against [[RB Leipzig]] during the [[2021–22 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] knockout round play-offs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/europa-league/r-sociedad-vs-leipzig/cronica/2022/02/24/6217c1f2e2704e089d8b45c0.html |title=Un sueño que se esfuma |publisher=Marca |language=es |date=24 February 2022 }}</ref> A month later, on 13 March, he scored his first La Liga goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Deportivo Alavés|Alavés]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/la-real-record-another-victory |title=La Real record another victory |publisher=Real Sociedad |date=13 March 2022 }}</ref> In October, he extended his contract with the club until 2027.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-espana.net/2022/10/15/real-sociedad-confirm-martin-zubimendi-extension-until-2027 |title=Real Sociedad confirm Martin Zubimendi extension until 2027 |publisher=Football España |date=15 October 2022 }}</ref> On 20 September 2023, he made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut in a 1–1 draw against [[Inter Milan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/real-sociedad-midfielder-zubimendi-so-proud-to-play-champions-league-in-my-hometown-4470888 |title=Real Sociedad midfielder Zubimendi: So proud to play Champions League in my hometown |publisher=Tribal Football |date=20 September 2023 }}</ref>

===Arsenal===
[[File:1 Martín Zubimendi arsenal 2025.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Zubimendi in Arsenal's 1-0 preseason friendly victory over AC Milan in Singapore]]
On 6 July 2025, Zubimendi signed for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on a long-term contract in a deal reportedly worth around €65m (£55.8m).<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 July 2025 |title=Martin Zubimendi signs for Arsenal |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/martin-zubimendi-signs-arsenal |access-date=6 July 2025 |website=Arsenal F.C. |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=de Roché |first1=Art |last2=Millar |first2=Colin |title=Arsenal confirm Martin Zubimendi signing from Real Sociedad |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6439762/2025/07/06/martin-zubimendi-arsenal-transfer-news/ |website=The New York Times |access-date=27 July 2025}}</ref> On 17 August, he made his debut for the club in a 1–0 win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the league.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 August 2025 |title=Calafiori strikes after goalkeeper’s error as Arsenal grind to win at Manchester United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/aug/17/manchester-united-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |access-date=23 August 2025 }}</ref> On 13 September, he netted his first goals by scoring a brace in a 3–0 victory over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Hytner |first=David |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/sep/13/arsenal-nottingham-forest-premier-league-match-report |title=Martín Zubimendi’s zest a bitter pill for Postecoglou as Arsenal batter Forest |publisher=The Guardian |date=13 September 2025 }}</ref> His first goal in that game would go on to win the [[Premier League Goal of the Month]] award for September 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Zubimendi wins Guinness Goal of the Month |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4437285/zubimendi-wins-guinness-goal-of-the-month |access-date=11 October 2025|date=10 October 2025|publisher=Premier League}}</ref> For his performances in September, Zubimendi was nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Help Martín Zubimendi win PL Player of the Month |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/help-martin-zubimendi-win-pl-player-month |website=Arsenal.com |access-date=5 October 2025}}</ref> He concluded his debut season by winning the [[2025–26 Premier League|Premier League]] title, becoming only the second player after [[Jens Lehmann]] in 2003–04 to achieve the feat while featuring in every league match.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wright |first=Nick |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13546939/crystal-palace-1-2-arsenal-champions-finish-historic-season-on-a-high-thanks-to-gabriel-jesus-and-noni-madueke-goals |title=Crystal Palace 1-2 Arsenal: Champions finish historic season on a high thanks to Gabriel Jesus and Noni Madueke goals |publisher=Sky Sports |date=24 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
Zubimendi represented the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain under-19]]s in a [[Exhibition match|friendly]] 2–1 loss to the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal under-19]]s on 15 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futboljuvenil.es/espana-sub-19-ofrece-una-buena-imagen-ante-portugal/|title=España Sub-19 ofrece una buena imagen ante Portugal|trans-title=Spain under-19 offer a good image against Portugal|publisher=Fútbol Juvenil|first=Cristina|last=Ripoll|language=es|date=15 November 2017|accessdate=14 June 2020}}</ref>

Due to the isolation of some national team players following the positive [[COVID-19]] test of [[Sergio Busquets]], Spain's under-21 squad were called up for the international friendly against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 8 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |title=Oficial {{!}} Lista de convocados para el encuentro ante Lituania |trans-title=Official {{!}} Squad list for the match against Lithuania |work=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |date=6 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |language=es |archive-date=8 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008070336/https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |url-status=dead }}</ref> Zubimendi made his senior debut in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/espana-vs-lituania/cronica/2021/06/08/60bfd85222601dc65d8b458f.html|title=Spain youngsters impress in Lithuania rout|website=MARCA|date=8 June 2021|accessdate=8 June 2021}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, he was selected in the 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2024 |title=Official {{!}} Final Spain squad for the Euro 2024 finals |url=https://rfef.es/en/noticias/final-spain-squad-for-the-euro-2024-finals |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |access-date=13 July 2024}}</ref> On 15 June, he made his first appearance in the Euros against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] as a substitute. He went on to play the full match against [[Albania national football team|Albania]] on 24 June, and came off the bench in both the semi-final victory over [[France national football team|France]] on 9 July and in [[UEFA Euro 2024 final|the final]] against [[England national football team|England]] on 14 July as Spain won the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b5e5c2b7b67-d5faab9be20b-1000--spain-2-1-england-late-oyarzabal-winner-earns-la-roja-reco/ |title=Spain 2–1 England: Late Oyarzabal winner earns La Roja record fourth EURO crown|website=UEFA|date=14 July 2024 |access-date=16 July 2024 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Zubimendi's versatile style of play draws comparisons to renowned players, notably [[Sergio Busquets]]. He showcases composure and control, guiding plays and adjusting the game's tempo. His role involves initiating plays from deep positions, displaying precise decision-making. Zubimendi's aptitude for receiving passes and creating space is reminiscent of Busquets, reflecting a deep understanding of the game and the art of crafting opportunities. Additionally, his technical abilities, including dribbling and deep runs, align with top midfielders, while his ball retention in tight spaces mirrors qualities seen in players like [[Xabi Alonso]] and [[David Silva]].<ref name="Lowe-2022" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Kemp |first=Jamie |url=https://theanalyst.com/eu/2022/10/zubimendi-the-real-sociedad-midfielder-finding-stardom-in-simplicity/ |title=Martín Zubimendi: The Real Sociedad Midfielder Finding Stardom in Simplicity |publisher=The Analyst |date=14 October 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Harris |first=Thom |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4600543/2023/06/13/martin-zubimendi-is-the-calm-and-methodical-heart-of-real-sociedads-midfield/ |title=Martin Zubimendi is the Gen-Z Sergio Busquets at the heart of Real Sociedad’s midfield |publisher=The Athletic |date=13 June 2023 }}</ref>

